					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2203795&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203757" alt="Kalinin" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2203795)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;" >Kalinin</a></span> <span class="odate time_1472667647 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">31 Aug 2016 18:20</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2581813">
									

<p>In general, I don't usually find poetry to be an appropriate medium for the wiki. This is not to say that it's impossible that I would support something like that ever, but I have yet to encounter an example of it that I like here. I find poetry to be far more intimate and emotionally relatable than most of the material that we work with here. It's that seriousness that makes poetry kind of cringey when it doesn't work well. I'll have more thoughts on this matter elsewhere.</p>
<p>This article isn't really changing my mind on that. Here, it's poetry as a &quot;guess which skip it is&quot; game more than anything else. I'm not really able to find a whole lot of emotional resonance in a giant murder lizard, and overall the subjects of the various stanzas are articles that have been covered so many times by now that I feel mostly boredom when I read anything about them. As an aside, I eagerly await the day when the site can put aside its obsession with Montauk, but I also realize that I'll be waiting a very long time.</p>
<p>Poetry has to carry a certain personal weight to it for it to be effective. And I'm not convinced the more well-worn, high profile monster articles and other mainstays are capable of being translated in such a manner as to impart that weight.</p>

							</div>

								
					
